First Call for papers Workshop on Spatio- Temporal Data Models and Languages Florence , Italy , August 30 - 31 , 1999 in conjunction with the 10 th International Conference on Database and Expert System applications ( DEXA'99 ) Florence , September 1 - 2 , 1999 The growing awareness of environmental issues and global change management has emphasized the need for rich , timely and flexible information systems capable of supporting decision making based on analysis of and reasoning on spatio-temporal data . At the same time the offer in GIS tools is rapidly changing , downsizing from large legacy-like systems to less ambitious but more manageable desktop GIS . These and other phenomena converge into promoting the idea of stronger user involvement in interactions with GIS . Consequently , data modeling , data languages and user interfaces gradually emerge as fundamental issues , where significant advances are needed to meet requirements of users whose profile and need have drastically cha ! ! nged . This workshop intends to promote the focus on data models and languages for spatial data , for temporal data , and for spatio-temporal processes . Topics of particular relevance include : ? conceptual or logical models for spatial and / or temporal data ? conceptual or logical models for spatio-temporal processes ? languages for data or metadata manipulation ? user interfaces ? models and languages for semantic interoperability ? usability assessment , in particular through significant applications ? domain specific models and languages ? innovative applications Submissions are solicited both in terms of original research contributions and practical experiments offering significant insights into responses to requirements . The workshop proceedings will be published by IEEE Computer Society PAPER SUBMISSION : The full paper submissions should not be more than 5000 words ( equivalent ten two columns pages ) in length . Papers will be reviewed by at least 3 program committee m ! ! embers for their technical merit , originality , significance , clarity , and relevance to the workshop . An abstract ( no more than 250 words in ASCII text ) of the paper , including the title of the paper , authors' names and 3 - 4 relevant keywords , should be sent via email to both the program chair and vice-chairs . Four copies of the full paper should be sent to either the program chair or vice-chairs to arrive before the deadline . Alternatively , an electronic version may be submitted and considered if printable . The title page must include the name and email address of the contact author . Authors of accepted paper will be required to register to the workshop and to the DEXA conference prior to publication of their paper .
